  abstract = {P{$>$}1. Functional traits are increasingly used to investigate community\textbackslash nstructure, ecosystem functioning or to classify species into functional\textbackslash ngroups. These functional traits are expected to be variable between and\textbackslash nwithin species. Intraspecific functional variability is supposed to\textbackslash ninfluence and modulate species responses to environmental changes and\textbackslash ntheir effects on their environment. However, this hypothesis remains\textbackslash npoorly tested and species are mostly described by mean trait values\textbackslash nwithout any consideration of variability in individual trait values.\textbackslash n2. In this study, we quantify the extent of intraspecific plant\textbackslash nfunctional trait variability, its spatial structure and its response to\textbackslash nenvironmental factors. Using a sampling design structured along two\textbackslash ndirect and orthogonal climatic gradients in an alpine valley, we\textbackslash nquantified and analysed the intraspecific variability for three\textbackslash nfunctional traits (height, leaf dry matter content and leaf nitrogen\textbackslash ncontent) measured on sixteen plant species with contrasting life\textbackslash nhistories.\textbackslash n3. Results showed a large variability of traits within species with\textbackslash nlarge discrepancies between functional traits and species. This\textbackslash nvariability did not appear to be structured within populations. Between\textbackslash npopulations, the overall variability was partly explained by the\textbackslash nselected gradients. Despite the strong effects of temperature and\textbackslash nradiation on trait intraspecific variability, the response curves of\textbackslash ntraits along gradients were partly idiosyncratic.\textbackslash n4.Synthesis. Giving a comprehensive quantification of intraspecific\textbackslash nfunctional variability through the analysis of an original data set, we\textbackslash nreport new evidence that using a single trait value to describe a given\textbackslash nspecies can hide large functional variation for this species along\textbackslash nenvironmental gradients. These findings suggest that intraspecific\textbackslash nfunctional variability should be a concern for ecologists and its\textbackslash nrecognition opens new opportunities to better understand and predict\textbackslash necological patterns in a changing environment. Further analyses are,\textbackslash nhowever, required to compare inter- and intraspecific variability.},
